# Part b) |x-1| + |x-5| = 2

---

## Step 1 — Find Turning Points

Two absolute values → Two turning points!

$$|x-1| → x = 1$$
$$|x-5| → x = 5$$

---

## Step 2 — Three Cases on Number Line

```
←————●————————●————→
     1                5

Case 1    Case 2    Case 3
 x < 1   1≤x<5      x ≥ 5
```

---

## Step 3 — Solve Each Case

### Case 1 (x < 1):
$$x-1 < 0 \quad x-5 < 0$$
$$|x-1| = -x+1 \quad |x-5| = -x+5$$

$$(-x+1) + (-x+5) = 2$$
$$-2x + 6 = 2$$
$$-2x = -4$$
$$x = 2 ❌$$
(x=2 is NOT < 1, so **invalid!**)

---

### Case 2 (1 ≤ x < 5):
$$x-1 ≥ 0 \quad x-5 < 0$$
$$|x-1| = x-1 \quad |x-5| = -x+5$$

$$(x-1) + (-x+5) = 2$$
$$4 = 2 ❌$$

This is **never true!** BUT wait...

> The left side always equals **4** in this range, but we need **2**. So **no solution here** either... 

Hmm! Let's check — actually 4 = 2 is impossible ❌

---

### Case 3 (x ≥ 5):
$$x-1 > 0 \quad x-5 ≥ 0$$
$$|x-1| = x-1 \quad |x-5| = x-5$$

$$(x-1) + (x-5) = 2$$
$$2x - 6 = 2$$
$$2x = 8$$
$$x = 4 ❌$$
(x=4 is NOT ≥ 5, so **invalid!**)

---

## Final Answer 📌

> **No solution exists!** ∅

---

## Why? Intuition 💡

```
|x-1| = distance from x to 1
|x-5| = distance from x to 5

Distance between 1 and 5 = 4

So |x-1| + |x-5| ≥ 4 ALWAYS!

It can NEVER equal 2 (which is less than 4)
```

---

## Key Insight 🧠

| Distance between turning points | Minimum possible sum |
|---|---|
| \|5 - 1\| = 4 | Sum is always ≥ 4 |
| We need sum = 2 | 2 < 4 → Impossible! |

